Five explosions shook Mt.
Pinatubo Friday, spreading ash over Clark, and as far away as  Manila.
Friday's blasts were part of the same eruption, the largest since Pinatubo awoke  Sunday from a 600-year slumber.
Typhoon Yunya, packing 60 MPH winds, hit the east  coast of Luzon, which includes Mt.
Pinatubo, but quickly weakened to a tropical storm.
The U.S. military began flying home some of the 28,000 Americans crowded into Subic  Bay Naval Base.
Philippine President Aquino dismissed as a fabrication a report that said  she had been warned volcanic damage could case a nuclear incident at Clark. 
